reviewText: This is used in our Digital SLR and it works great. No lag and there is a ton of storage.  Otherwise not much to review, it's an SD card with 32GB of storage.

I own a point and shoot and a high-end DSLR from Nikon and this card is equally good for both the cameras (well... in mots of the situations!!!). Being a class 10 SDHC card, it can take multiple shots at once and is ideal for 1080p movies. I generally shoot RAW on DSLR and the image size is quite large (25-35 MB) for RAW files. This card will hold a lesser number of images than a 32GB or a 64GB card. But i prefer carrying around more number of cards with less capacity (8 or 16 GB) that the cards with large capacity. The idea is that in case you loose a card or it goes corrupt, you loose lesser number of images and dont loose the images for one whole shoot or an entire trip.The only time when its not a good idea is when you are trying to take a panorama shot wherein you have to click a large number of images rapidly and that when the buffering/writing capacity of class 10 cards becomes a limitation. Having said that, how often does one shoot a panorama !!!!On a financial side, its a great product at unbelievable rate. I haven't found any other retail store selling this card at a lesser price (not even 80% of the price at Amazon).I would strongly recommend this card for any type of digital camera you have and that takes SDHC cards as memory device.
summary: Great product at a great price by a trusted name !!!

I have a Transcend 8 GB SDHC card that works pretty well for my application. So I bought this 32 GB card to give it a try. There were some reviews saying that it is not really a class 10 card in terms of writing speed. So I did some quick tests. I copied a folder containing 766 files of various sizes and total 20.4 GB onto the card. That took 40 minutes and 59 seconds --> average 8.5 MB/sec. Then I copied 355 files (9.4 GB). That took 18 minutes and 8 seconds --> average 8.9 MB/sec. So in both tests the write speed is a little bit shy from the nominal 10 MB/sec but not too much off. Reading back and binary comparing with the original files from the first test took 28 minutes and 21 seconds. So the reading speed is 12.3 MB/sec.
summary: Transcend 32 GB Class SDHC 10: real life speed test

reviewText: When traveling and taking movies in addition to still shots, it is a wise investment to have a big capacity and fast SD card for your camera. Re-inserting the card carefully into the camera a second time then worked fine. But this experience made me realize that it is important to carry a second SD card with you, and also it is risky to not download and back up your photos on-going, even while traveling--in case a memory card ever fails on you.
summary: High capacity, high speed, good for HD 1080p

reviewText: Previously aWintec Filemate 16 GB Professional Class 10 Secure Digital SDHC Carduser, I ended up giving that card to my Mom for her new digital camera after discovering an old 2GB Polaroid brand card was what she was using.  Continually getting poor quality shots, I thought it was her camera and had purchased her a new one.  While the camera wasn't the best, the card was the real issue.I bought a second Wintec for me, but then read the reviews on this Transcend card and decided to purchase both.I knew I wanted a Class 10 SDHC at the right price to boost the performance of myOlympus SP-800UZ 14MP Digital Camera with 30x Wide Angle Dual Image Stabilized Zoom and 3.0 inch LCD. As with the Wintec Professional one, I was pleasantly surprised by this Transcend's performance in both this camera, myRicoh GR DIGITAL IV US 10 MP Digital Camera with 1x Optical Zoom and 3-Inch LCD screen (Black)and in myNikon Coolpix S6000 14.2 MP Digital Camera with 7x Optical Vibration Reduction (VR) Zoom and 2.7-Inch LCD (Silver).After some informal testing of with similar shots at night, I concluded the Transcend card is just a hair faster than the Wintec.  Both are very good for everyday use, but some may prefer the Transcend card despite the small bump in price.Photos had been coming up blurry and the time the zoom took to focus was lagging with another card (Class 4):SanDisk Ultra 16 GB Class 4 SDHC Flash Memory Card SDSDRH-016G-A11.  With the Transcend card, those issues are almost completely gone and macro shots work much better too.Worked well taking video as well.Very pleased with this card - highly recommend it for faster, clearer shots taken with your digital camera.
summary: A nice tweak for digital camera performance

reviewText: I chose this card because it was the cheapest class 10 I could find and apparently Amazon promotes it, so it couldn't be that bad.I'm giving it 4 stars only because I know there are other cards with better speeds.I'm not dissapointed with it at all, it is pretty fast, lets you take a lot of pictures (approx. 550 raw files with an 18MP DSLR).I would recommend this card to any photographer or anyone who uses windows readboost technology (who uses that feature?)

In May, 2011, we went on a Moscow - Volga - St. Petersburg tour, equipped with two Canon cameras - mine an SD 780 IS, which works perfectly. I purchased and installed a Transcend HC 8GB memory chip in my camera. The camera appeared to work normally - taking at least 550-600 shots with plenty of memory left - I even took 2-3 minutes of video.Unfortunately, when downloaded to my home PC - only about 160 pictures were available to view - I was stunned to say the least - this was a once-in-a-lifetime tour - the photos are irreplaceable.I called a local camera shop, which said they might be able to  recover the rest. Well they recovered another 200 or so (charged me about $45), but the first three days of our vacation's really interesting photos, they could not recover.However, they had a recommendation, another company nearby, which does digital work for the Department of Defense, might be able to help. I called them and they quoted a price of $500 dollars over the phone to recover all my photos - if unsuccessful there would be no charge. Money doesn't grow on trees - I'm mulling it over. But I highly recommend NOT buying any Transcend memory chip
summary: Major failure: Transcend HC 8GB memory card

Okay, usually you review these things for speed and longevity if at all. There are definitely more exciting products to review. I usually get Sandisk products, and am especially fond of their CF cards. But when I got my Canon 60D and Canon PowerShot D20, I picked up a few of these smaller Transcend cards on sale. I'm also not a huge fan of larger cards for a variety of reasons, so keep handfuls of them around at about 16GB.Anyway, apparently when I was on vacation I popped one of these cards in one of the half dozen pockets of my cargo shorts when it was full-up, in it's little plastic case and promptly forgot about it. Since it's so small, it went unnoticed when doing a cursory pocket search before hitting the laundry. It got washed, dried and was in the process of being ironed when my wife noticed a bulge that wouldn't iron out. Yikes! Darned if all the photos weren't still accessible, and since then it's read and written just fine. I doubt that a CF card could have made the journey, but considering it got a soaking (even in the case) and a rather toasty drying, not too bad!Other than the washing, these cards have done their job and are fast - I have no problems going well above my rated burst speed and duration on a Canon 60D. I've shot well over 80 images (JPEG) without hitting the end of my buffer. Video has never been an issue. As far as I can tell, they easily match my Class 10 Sandisk Extreme cards (8 & 16GB). For doing what it's supposed to do, doing it well, and surviving above and beyond the call of duty I give it 5 stars.*** Update 11/26/12 ***The card is still chugging away. I've been sure to use it as my #1 walk around and test card (not "for pay" card). It's worked so long and done the read/write/format for both photos and video thing for so long I'm almost ready to just put it back into general circulation again. Basically, I trust it!*** Update 06/20/13 ***Ditto last update

I bought one of these back in mid-2011, and used it as secondary storage for my laptop for about 18 months, until replacing it with a larger one this past fall.  I still used this one, however, for data I didn't need readily accessible all the time, but was too big to keep on a cloud drive of some sort.Well, around Christmas 2012, I put some save files for a couple games on it, thinking I might want to play something while visiting family, and then forgot the card in my pocket when we got home, and I did the laundry.  I found its little plastic case when I pulled the laundry out of the dryer, but the card itself never turned up.  I figured the case must have opened in my pocket and the card fallen out somewhere, and wrote it off as lost.Fast forward a few more months - just this evening, as I was finishing up the laundry, I noticed something wedged into the inside of the dryer door.  Pulled it loose, and lo and behold, it is my old 32gb SD card.  It's still intact, too!  I figure the thing must be ruined by now, after all, it went through the wash, and several dozen times through the dryer.  But what the hell, I plugged it in anyway, and amazingly enough, the files are all apparently fine.So Transcend makes some pretty durable solid-state memory.

While you can find cheaper options, and you can find faster options, it's hard to beat Transcend for a reasonably priced, reasonably fast card.  I've got a few of these and none has ever failed on me, so while I'm sure I will at some point, they're good enough for my needs.

reviewText: I bought 2 of these and used the first one for a photo shoot.  Afterwards the card said it needed to be formatted.  I had to pay for memory recovery to recover the photos sense no card reader would read it.  I thought it was a one time thing sense I have owned Transcend cards before and have NEVER had any problems.  I formatted the card and carried on.  A few days later I was shooting a wedding reception.  45 minuets into the event the card said it needed to be formatted again and wouldn't let me continue to use it.  I decided I had a faulty card and popped the second one in.  After two more hours the second card did the same thing.  Cost me $150 in total to recover all the photos as well as having to run out during the reception to buy another card quickly so I could finish photographing the event.  If it was just very random faulty cards then I must have had REALLY bad luck.  As it is, 2/2 is a pretty bad record.  I'm moving on the kingston or sandisk instead of taking the risk.

In both tests, I used the Transcend card reader (Transcend Information USB 3.0 Card Reader (TS-RDF5K)) and attempted to transfer 7GB of data. I purchased this Transcend Card to go with a new digital camera along with a faster version from S**disk.  I have not conducted any bench mark testing (other reviewers have so keep for hard numbers if you want).  What I can tell you is that this card transfers (both read and write) about twice as fast as an 8GB class 6 I have but not as fast as my S**disk Extreme Class 10 16GB.  However, for the price this is a very good value if you do not need the bleeding edge speed of other cards.  Most people do not need the highest speed cards as the hardware they are using them in is slower than this card.  The main exceptions to this are DSLR cameras and computers newer than ~2011.  Even in those devices the actual transfer speed increase with the faster cards is fairly minor and most people will never notice it.This is my fifth Transcend SD or micro SD card in the recent past.  All but one of them are still working with the oldest working one being a 128 MB ~8 years old card with very heavy daily use including being inserted and removed from card readers at least every few days.  the one that no longer works was a 64 MB micro SD card my wife got with her LG Musiq cell phone ~10 years ago.  That one met with the ewaste recycler due to storage capacity but did not fail.  Alo note worthy is that I have only ever had one SD card fail due to use, and this was a Kodak branded card bought for a digital picture frame MANY years ago.
summary: Good Card But Faster Cards Exist

reviewText: Got this mostly for the size, but was hoping for some better speed in my Nikon D7000 compared to the 4GB Sandisk Extreme Class 4 cards I already had. No difference, in fact in some cases the Sandisk cards are about a second faster.Here's what I did to test:Shoot 9 continuous shots (fills the buffer) with the camera set to 5fps, 14-bit RAW.As soon as the last shot completes, time how long it takes to clear the buffer (until a 9 appears in the viewfinder again indicating you can shoot 9 shots).After 5 runs apiece shooting the same subject and lighting conditions the Class 10 Transcend card and the Class 4 SanDisk card come in at exactly the same - around 11 seconds.I got this more for the storage, but if speed matters to you stick with one of the better brands like SanDisk.
summary: Same speed as 4GB Class 4 Sandisk Extreme card

I bought this card for my Canon T3i. I have used it for stills and video. I am happy with the card overall, and will order Transcend again for stills. Video however left me wanting more. Just seems slow to say class 10.With stills I shoot RAW. I went through up to 5 shots in continuous mode before having the camera slow and then up to 15 shots before it stopped to let the buffer empty. I was trying to shoot the hummingbirds around our house. As a result I lost a few good shots. The write speed was not all that good for action shooting. However, still shots were clear and perfect in single mode, and the card had no problem keeping up with write as long as the shutter released was pressed for each shot.With video, even thought it is a Class 10 card, I was having trouble with stuttering. I could not shoot more than 3 minutes at a time without running into pausing issues on the developed video, and eventually spent the money and bought a Sandisk Extreme card to replace it for video and action shots.I am happy with the card over all for my still work and portrait shots. I will order this one again to use for that purpose, but if you are looking to catch that perfect moment when you son kicks the wining goal, you don't want to slip on the shutter release, or have the buffer fill up on you. I did include some images I managed to capture with this card though, and I would recommend it for hobbyists and again for portraits, landscapes, and students.

March 13, 2014 OK, I tried using this SD card while recording in FXP mode on my Canaon Vixia HF20 camcorder. WARNING! WARNING! WARNING! This card does NOT record in FXP or MXP mode on the Canon Vixia HF20. You will get a message, "Cannot record movies in MXP/FXP mode on this memory card." My question is, "Why not?" I am so upset about this-more because I have had a previous card of this type and did not notice this limitation. The Canon Vixia HF20 also will NOT allow you to copy either video in either mode from the camcorder to the SD card. You CAN record onto the CDHC card in XP mode, though. I don't like the limitation and do not understand the limitation for this card in this camcorder. Another drawback is that when you attempt to read the memory card to check its specs, you will not see the card's class. It only shows "CLASS -". I CAN use this card with my Canon Vixia HF M31 camcorder. So, the limited use of this card is based on the camcorder's capacity to use it, for whatever reason. I can record FXP or MXP video on SanDisk class 4 SDHC cards with no problem.December 9, 2013 I am satisfied with this flash memory. I bought a 8 GB SD card with a Speed Class of 10, because I use it to shoot Full HD video on my Sony XR150 camcorder. The larger the Class number, the greater the write speed of the SD card. Therefore this card can achieve a write speed of 10 Megabytes/second (or 80 Megabits/second).This is in accordance to recommendation by the Secure Digital Association (sdcard.org):Class 2 : H.264 video recording, MPEG-4, MPEG-2 video recordingClass 4: MEPG-2 (HDTV) video recording, DSC consecutive shootingClass 6: Mega-pixel DSC consecutive shooting, professional video cameraClass 10: Full HD video recording, HD still consecutive shootingWhen it comes to SD cards, other than SanDisk, Transcend is another brand that I trust.
summary: You Need Class 10 SD If You Shoot Full HD Video

The two higher quality bitrates MXP (24mbps) and FXP (17mbps) will not record. Very disappointing.Also, when you select Memory Card Info from the menu, it does not recognize the card as Class 10. It says it's 32gb and displays all the other info, but not its class speed. The manual clearly states the HFS100 will record on Class 4 "or higher" SDHC cards. Except in the case of Transcend, it won't work. I really wanted to use this for long runs in my HFS100. The camera is clearly capable of handling 32GB cards, just not Transcend Class 10 32GB cards. According to Canon, there are no firmware updates announced for this camera. Bummer.Fortunately, the card seems to work fine in the little GoPro Hero HD camcorder, so I guess that's where it will reside.If you go to the Transcend website, they don't even list this part number. I bought a 64 GB Transcend SD (SDXC) card, had problems with it on a Vista computer, and sent it back for an exchange.The second card I received exhibits the same problem.This SD card arrives with exFAT formatting. It works perfectly in the Windows 8 and Windows 7 computers I have at home.At my office, I have an older Vista computer. According to the exFAT spec, exFAT should work with Vista as long as Service Pack 1 is installed. Neither of these cards did, however. Instead, there is a message stating the card must be formatted before it can be used. If I try to format it in Vista, NTFS, exFAT and FAT (not FAT32) are provided as options. It won't format the card using NTFS or exFAT and if you format it as FAT, the card only shows about 4 megabytes of memory rather than 64 GB.I rated this at 3 Stars since I don't have another Vista computer to experiment on. It could be something unique to the one Vista SP1 computer I did try. That computer has no problem reading other cards, though. A Transcend 16 GB (SDHC) card formatted as FAT32 works great, and I've used all sorts of USB flash drives, compact flash cards and so forth without any problems for years.I had intended to use this Transcend card to transfer large video files back and forth from home to work, and also to backup my music collection. I wasted $47, and I see the price has since gone UP to $55.I'd suggest trying another brand.
summary: My Vista Service Pack 1 Computer Won't Read Or Format This Card

Using the same brand (Transcend) 400x CF card, the camera can take 20 photos and it takes only 10 seconds to write these to the card. In other words, this card is about 3 times slower. As long as you are not too worried about speed but need lots of storage, this is a good card, but when it comes to fast shooting, this will slow you down.

This is absurd.  My Transcend  8 Gb Class 10 Flash memory card just failed after only two months (I got the dreaded "Insert SD card again" error message)!  To be certain that the problem was the Transcend card, I inserted the failed card in a different digital camera and it still didn't work (same message)....then I inserted a different card into the original camera, and that card worked fine.  Knowing that the card was the problem, I called Transcend's support line, where I was told that the only way to get a replacement was to go online and follow this  "protocol":Step 1: Log in to your accountStep 2: Submit your RMA Application FormStep 3: Review the RMA Application FormStep 4: Send your product with the printed RMA formNow, this card cost me only $8.95 and I'm convinced the lesson here is that "cheap is dear", and so now I'm only buying SanDisk memory for my cameras.The reason for this is, by the way, NOT just because this card failed in mere weeks (and I've apparently lost all pictures stored on it), but that I would have to go through all the above steps, after which I would have to package the card, drive to the post office to mail it to Transcend, pay for the mailing and confirmation fee, then drive back home and WAIT god knows how long for a new card to arrive.  The cost to me in time and actual cash would be more than the original cost of the card, plus I'd probably have to wait weeks to get the new one.I would much prefer paying a little more for a SanDisk card that is more reliable.....but wait, actually I think I'm willing to pay more than just a "little" more to get a more reliable card, given the value of pictures or video that I could lose next time, if I stick with Transcend!
summary: I highly recommend avoiding Transcend flash memory cards!

I ordered this along with my Nikon D3200. Started taking pictures while I was out on a short vacation. When I came back and tried to transfer the pictures from the memory card to the computer, mostly all the pictures were corrupted and broken. They either had bands or were cut and rearranged or had grey areas or some other color tint. Overall pathetic. Almost 40% of the pics were like this. The pictures looked perfect in the camera and also in the thumbnail view in the computer but when i opened them to anything bigger than thumbnail it looked disappointing . I lost so many valuable photographs.I reformatted the card using the camera ,took some snaps, again the same problem.I reformatted in computer , again the same problem, then i reformatted many times in the camera, but no change. I was thinking that there was some problem with the camera. Then I borrowed another memory card from someone and took snaps with that. Wow everything was perfect , I took at least 100 snaps and all were fine.So it was the memory card not the camera.I contacted amazon and they replaced the same card, I did not want a refund I just wanted a working memory card. I'm sure that this Transcend makes wonderful cards , its just that I got a bad piece. Also I contacted Transcend, and they were willing to replace it or refund as per the warranty policy. Amazon replaced my card with a 2 day shipping for free, without it even being in the original packing. Hopefully the one which comes now is working fine.I'm just sad that I lost so many pics due to a bad card. I would recommend everyone who buy this or any other card , to test it completely by taking at least 50 to 100 pics and transferring them to the computer before taking it out on an important task. Hope this helps !!I would add to this once i get a new card.

reviewText: A class 10, 8gb memory card for this price? And the reviews on this are great. I haven't done speed tests or anything, but haven't had any trouble recording full-HD recording on my camera (1080p), which is really all that matters to me. 8gb is an ideal size; I don't want one card that's 16gb, prefer 2 that are 8. That way I can put one in the computer and have the other in the camera at all times. Take one out, put one in. You won't forget your memory card that way. Of course if you plug the camera directly to the computer it won't be a problem then, either... Ok, well if one goes bad you'll still have one. Ha. Did you know SD cards are waterproof (up to 72 hours in 1 meter of SALT or fresh water), withstand temperatures from -13F to 185F, can withstand drops up to 16 feet, vibration proof, survives being run over by a 5 ton delivery truck, and magnet proof? Oh, and x-ray proof, and can withstand 500Gs of shock. in case that matters. Just found that out, kinda good to know if I drop my camera 16 feet in Alaska (most of the year) and the memory card pops out and into a puddle, gets run over by a truck and after all that I forget that it's in my pocket when I get an x-ray, it will still be ok. I wonder if it would survive being swallowed... If you get the urge to test that, you might wanna try it with a microSD card. Just a thought. If you have incriminating pictures on your camera, it might be good to know if you can swallow it and it'll survive. Just sayin.

reviewText: Of course, any chip could hold an impossibly huge amount, but it is A Transcend, so it is reliable, inexpensive, rock solid.

I have had this memory card for about 3 months.  It worked great for full HD videos and 5.3 frame per minute stills on my Canon EOS 60D camera.  It is everything I could hope for in this large SDHC Flash Memory Card.The Bad News!I installed the card and my camera tells me it can't write to it.  When I removed the memory card I noticed that the little yellow write protect switch in the side of the card was missing!  What?  How could it be missing and where is it!!  The card housing was never glued properly.  There were two small spots that were holding the housing halves together.  These came apart enough to allow the write protect switch to fall out, making the card unusable.  Panic set in worried about where the little yellow switch may have ended up.  Was it in my camera SD card slot or maybe in my laptop?  I had no idea.  Long story short, I found it on the floor.I thought about sending it in to Transcend for a replacement, but I didn't trust the replacement would be any better than this one.  I ended up doing my own micro surgery on it, carefully replacing the write protect switch and than carefully re-gluing the housing back together. It once again works fine.Bottom line,  I don't think I'll buy another from them.  If I did, I'd check the case carefully to make sure it is really glued together well.  I shoot weddings, and it would be embarrassing to say the least to find out my camera or memory card would quit working due to improvidently glued case or because the write protect switch ended up stuck in the camera.
summary: The Housing Became Unglued - Not Good

reviewText: This was a great buy and works perfectly in my camera. The speed at which it operates is very good.
I bought this card for Nikon S6200 camera and it works very well without any issues. It been more than 6 months and I didnt see any issues yet.

As a wedding photographer, I don't need the fastest cards in the world, but I do need a lot of them.  Primarily that's because I don't format a card until the job is delivered.  (This serves as one of my four data backups.)  If I were shooting on cameras that only take a single memory card, I'd be inclined to spend the extra money on Lexar Pro or Sandisk Pro cards.  However, I use these cards in my Canon 5D mk III, which writes every shot to a CF card and an SD card for extra backup.When my 5D mk III was my primary body, I looked for the best performing Class 10 cards I could find.  (The 5d3 will happily use UHS-1 cards, but only at a Class 10 speed, so you're really only buying a card that will download to your computer faster over USB3.)  The 5d3's buffer only holds about 12 RAW files, and waiting for the camera to flush the data to the card is painfully slow.  (Not a problem if you ONLY shoot on the CF card, but again, backup is critical to me.)  Some class 10 cards can perform around 19MB/s write, but not these.  These meet only the minimum class 10 write spec of about 10MB/s.Now that the Canon 1DX is my primary body the slower performance is fine - when the 5d3 caps out, I just switch back to my 1DX while it flushes data.  If the 5d3 is your primary, and you get stuck waiting for the camera to flush after a burst, I'd recommend spending a little more so the camera can finish writing files faster.Here are the read/write scores of two identical 16GB SDHC Transcend cards:Card 1 Read: 21.36MB/sCard 1 Write: 10.66MB/sCard 2 Read: 21.82MB/sCard 2 Write: 10.45MB/sThese numbers are from a test that filled the entire card to capacity, then read that data back.  Not mind blowing, but I only use these smaller 16GB cards on short projects like engagement sessions, so they're fine for that purpose.

For my wedding back in May 2012, I received one of those LCD digital picture frames from one of my previous coworkers. I previously purchased a Transcend 8GB Class 6 SDHC memory cardTranscend 8 GB Class 6 SDHC Flash Memory Card with USB Card Reader TS8GSDHC6-P2for another LCD digital picture frame but now since I had two frames, I now needed a 2nd SDHC card. For those not familiar with the brand, the market is dominated by the names of Sandisk and PNY and it can be quite confusing on which is a "better" product.First and foremost, if you don't have an SDHC card read on your PC or laptop, you need some kind of card reader.  Luckily my past purchase came with a USB adapter so this time around, all I had to do is just purchase the card itself.  Although I paid nearly the same price as my previous purchase, the reason for similarity in price is due to the fact that this card (being reviewed) is a Class 10 SDHC card. Class ratings have a specific purpose. The SD Association defines standard speed classes indicating minimum performance to record video. Both read and write speeds must exceed the specified value. These are defined in terms of suitability for different applications:Class 2 for SD video recordingClass 4 and 6 for HD ~ Full HD video recording,Class 10 for Full HD video recording and HD still consecutive recording.The specification defines these classes in terms of performance curves that translate into the following minimum read-write performance levels on an empty card:Class Minimum performanceClass 2 2 MB/secClass 4 4 MB/secClass 6 6 MB/secClass 10 10 MB/secSo you may be asking "why did you buy a Class 10 card specifically for a digital picture frame, which wouldn't dare need to meet those speed performances"?  While your question may be valid, remember I'm using these for pictures... hundreds if not thousands of pictures... that need to be transferred from my PC to the card itself.  The class speed specification also applies to files being copied to/from the card itself. So with that said, I got a class 10 because the price is fairly cheap (cheaper than when I looked in 2011) plus I'm "future proofing" myself in the event that I want to use this card for another purpose (perhaps a future digital SLR camera).Doing simple transfer tests, I did achieve slightly over a 10 MB/sec transfer rate while copying pictures to this card. While others may boast that the Sandisk high speed cards are able to transfer faster, they also cost an arm and a leg. Transcend is the only card that has decent performance at a very affordable price. I know I only own two of them, but because of the value I can easily see myself looking to buy more of them in the future.Recommended.
summary: Repeat Buyer of Transcend Memory Cards - Works Great

reviewText: I have 10 of these cards in my camera bag and I have to confess that while I try to take good care of them, sometimes when I'm traveling or shooting, I'm not that kind to them. I'm very impressed then that these cards are extremely reliable and tough. I can't imagine why people would spend two or three times as much on a card. Also, even though I write photo books for a living including [[...]], I have to say that the whole card-speed issue is a mystery wrapped in a riddle. Manufacturers have not made any effort to establish a consistent and reliable method for comparing the read/write speed of various cards. The speed rating system is confusing, at best. With almost all (not all) cameras, these cards will perform more quickly than your camera's buffer can keep up with. It's the camera that is usually the slow link. Also, many cameras don't have the capability to take advantage of very fast cards, so be sure to read your camera's manual before you spend a boatload of money on super-fast cards.Overall I think these Transcend cards are a great bargain and I use them daily and have for years. Don't get snowed by advertising claims from the biggies--for the most part they're blowing smoke. One thing though, unless you are using these cards for shooting video when you might need huge storage, I'd stick to a max of 16 or even 8 gigs. If you take a 32 gig card on vacation and lose it, yikes, you've lost a whole trip. When I'm on a travel assignment, I shoot 8 gig cards and download them (and burn them to dvd) at the end of the day--and then a few times a week I overnight the actual cards home.
summary: These cards are great: fast, reliable and a bargain

That may seem like a fairly long time, but compared to just about any other transfer of 10GB, this is blazing fast. The only faster data transfer I can think of is USB3.0, but nobody uses that anyway hahaWrite - I can fill my camera's buffer if I do a lot of bursting in RAW+JPEG, but that's only if I shoot 20+ images at 16MP, and do it about as fast as my camera shoots.  If HD video is your thing, even 100Mb/s bitrates move onto the card smoothly, no lag etc.Capacity - I have a hard time filling this one up - I usually shoot my battery dry before my SD card.  Once formatted, the usable space is 15.00GB.Shipping - It shipped quickly and I got it on the first day in the window (3 days after shipping)Overall a product meeting expectations, a great deal as well.  I would recommend this to anyone with a use for fast transfer SD cards.
summary: Great Class 10 for Photography and Video

reviewText: I wanted the cheapest 16 GB card I could get, and settled on this one. I was looking for a Class 10 SDHC to be used in a dash cam. The camera requires Class 6 or higher, but the prices for Class 10 cards were not very much higher. There are lower prices to be had, but generally attached to very little recognized brands that have worrying reviews concerning their reliability. From a brief survey of review sites, I get the impression that Transcend represents a lower-priced but still "legitimate" brand.There are faster/"better" cards out there, but if you want "good enough for lowest cost" with a reasonable expectation that it will continue to work, this is the best I could find.
summary: Good value for a name brand

reviewText: While the Transcend SDHC memory card is designated Class 10 it comes nowhere close to the write speed of a Sandisk SDHC Class 10 memory card. Testing the time it takes from when the picture is taken on my Panasonic G5 until the camera is done writing a RAW/JPEG combo (21.3MB in size) the Transcend performed closer to what I'd expect a Sandisk Class 4 memory card to write.I compared the write time of the Transcend Class 10 to a Sandisk Class 10 (45MB/S), Sandisk Class 6 (20MB/S), and Sandisk Class 2. Taking multiple images with each card and averaging the write time gave the following results:Sandisk Class 10: 3.3 secondsSandisk Class 6: 4.2 secondsTranscend Class 10: 6.2 secondsSandisk Class 2: 7.9 secondsWhile the Transcend is an affordable SDHC option, being less expensive than the Sandisk Class 10, and likely sufficient as a back up memory card which I will be using it for, if write speed is an important consideration the extra money is well spent on getting the Sandisk Class 10.
summary: Tests Show Closer To The Write Time Of A Sandisk Class 4

reviewText: I was starting to finally reach the space limit of the 2GB card that came with my 3DS back in October 2012, and I decided that I would get a card I stand no chance of filling up any time soon.  I saw the prices on SD cards were kind of low, so I went for the 16GB class 10 card by Transcend (TS16GSDHC10E), and I am glad I did.  The card gets me about 15-20 mbps write speed (35mbps read speed) according to Win8, and it worked almost out-of-box with the 3DS.  I say 'almost' because I had to use the SDHC format tool before the 3DS would understand the card was there.Anyway, this is a great card for Nintendo 3DS.  I highly recommend it.  It makes the space a lot higher (14.7 gigs after format), and it makes booting the 3DS menu a lot quicker because of the larger space allowance and the higher read/write speeds.  Be warned, though, that transferring 3DS files to a new card can be risky.  Save a backup of your data in a folder on your computer for safe keeping.The card also seems to work well in both of my digital cameras, but I hardly ever use my cameras, so I cannot give a worthy opinion about long term camera use.  It should work fairly well, though, and the price is very nice.  It's worth a shot at only $12.72!  Plus, Transcend is a good brand in my opinion.  I have yet to get a product by them that was below standards.  This card met all my expectations and even surprised me a little at such a low price. I am a very happy customer. :)
summary: Very fast card, great for a Nintendo 3DS, also works well for cameras.

reviewText: They are generally cheaper than SanDisk (though not always) and they have a warranty in case something goes wrong.  I purchase SD cards for my camera and camcorder, my kids' cameras and camcorders and my dad's camera and camcorder...I buy a lot of SD cards, but now I only buy Transcend cards. Last summer I got a new Sony camcorder and a new Linux digital camera for a 6 1/2 week camping trip to Alaska and as usual, I bought the cheapest class 10 card I found...except this time, the cheapest was not Transcend. It took pictures and video just fine all through the trip in my Linux camera, but after we got home, I couldn't download it to my computer! I was scared to death that we had lost all our pictures of the amazing wildlife and incredible scenery! I did find a software product (for about $50) online and was able to get most everything off the card, but I don't even know what I might still be missing. At the time I purchased this other card, I also got one for my dad and he had the same problem. So now I have to bring his card to my computer (or my laptop to him) to get as much as we can off his card. I have never once had an issue with a Transcend card not being recognized by a device or had trouble getting things from a Transcend card to my computer. I will not stray again, it's not worth the risk. If I can't afford a SanDisk, I'm getting Transcend!

I bought this to use with my new Canon 60D camera, which just arrived a few days ago.  With 18 megapixels, set at the highest image quality, saving as both RAW and JPEG, this card still holds approximately 950 images. Set on RAW only, I had no issues with writing speed when shooting 8fps for short bursts (roughly 2 second bursts), so JPEG will be a no brainer.  However I have not shot bursts while recording in both RAW and JPEG, so I can't comment on that.What I can say is that I initially thought I may need to step up to an Extreme series SD card for writing speed, but as it stands now I think I'll be happy with these (I'm buying more) cards.

I purchased these through J&R; Music and Computer World via Amazon a couple of months ago as preparation for my Paris vacation.  I owned a Class 6 Transcend 8GB card for a long time and it was fast and never had any problems, so I figured I should get two of these class 10 cards as backup as i wasn't going to be bringing my laptop with me.Despite these being class 10 and therefore supposed to be faster, the ones i received are SLOWER than my class 6.  I tested both cards and took various photos around the house and noticed there's a distinct 2 second or so lag after i take a photo.  With my class 6 card, I can take a photo and immediately change to view mode to look at what i just took a pic of.  With the class 10 card when I do this, I get a message saying something like "recording, please wait" for around 2 seconds before my photo appears.  When taking photos too, with the class 10 there's a very obvious 2 second lag after each photo.I kept both cards because I was paranoid i'd run out of space on my class 6 card and i already tossed the packaging (returns seems to require original intact packaging?  how does that work if i obviously have to open it to test the card? O__o ).  Ultimately my single class 6 8gb card from years ago was plenty for my trip so these two cards were a waste purchase...probably giving one to mom when i buy her a new camera later.in any case, these cards are oddly far slower than my class 6 transcend 8gb cards.  I haven't used it long enough to know if there are any other issues (such as ones described by other reviewers that it corrupts after a few months of usage).

Great fidelity.  I have always trusted Transcend.  The only thing is it seems to take a bit longer (fraction of a second) longer in recording images.  Would not have noticed, but I had to change SDHC cards while shooting.  The older SDHC 16GB Sandisk 16 GB Ultra Series Class 10 SDHC (purchased from Costco) card was faster.  I don't exactly know why.

reviewText: I got 2 of these cards.  I have a Windows 7 tablet, along with 2 old MP3 players, and a newer, cheap mp3 player with speakers.  I wanted these cards to run on the Windows 7 tablet, and hopefully, the MP3 players.First of all, this card comes pre-formatted in the 'exFAT' format, which I have never dealt with before.  I looked at the formatting options, and this card can be formatted in NTFS or exFAT.  So you cannot format this in FAT32 format in Windows 7.  Well, Thanks to a tip from O. Shamayev, I did a websearch on 'forcing fat32 format on SDXC card' led me to a free utility that does the trick, and I now have a 64GB SDXC card that's in fat32 format and works on all my devices, even my 5 year old Cowon D2 mp3 player!It works great!  I'm currently transferring about 32GB of data to the 64GB SDXC card, and it's taking about 40 minutes.  Speed is good for me.  I'm using one of these cards in my tablet, and have the second card loaded with music and it works in all my mp3 players!Highly recommend this card for the price!

reviewText: I often get the infamous "Video recording has stopped automatically." I never shot much videos so I didn't care, and I always chalked it up as something I'm doing wrong on my end. But from here on out, I will need to record videos, and so these pass few days, I've been researching why this is happening. People say you need at least a class 6, and that a class 10 should be plenty fast. Not only that, many Canon 60D owners have reported having good luck with this Transcend model. So it's perplexing. I'm a 60D owner and this card does not shoot videos. Well, let me be more specific... It does not shoot videos consistently. I have to keep pushing record again and again and again, and once in awhile, it will record without stopping. Anyway, I've put in an order for a 32gb Amazon Basics and a Sony brand as well. Lets see if I have any luck with those. The "MOST HELPFUL CRITICAL REVIEW" also has issues with the Canon 60D, so I guess I'm not alone. That's a good thing because then you don't have to worry about whether or not your 60D is faulty. I'm glad I know it's the card, not the camera.

reviewText: I've seen a lot of back and forth about data rates on Class 10 SDHC cards, so I decided to run some simple copy/paste tests.  No sophisticated test software was used.I placed 183 Camera RAW files in a folder on my iMac PowerPC (4,574,838,784 bytes per "Get Info"), inserted the cards one at a time (four of them) into my SanDisk card reader, created a single folder on the card (called "SpeedTest"), and copied the 183 files to that folder.  I timed the copy times using my trusty SportLine Alpha 461 electronic stop watch (yes, the one I got for my daughter's swim meets, in case the touch pads croaked out).  And then copied the same 183 files back to a test folder on my iMac.  I put the test values in a spreadsheet.Write rates as follows:  average of the four cards, 14.81 MB/s (range from 14.62 to 14.95 MB/s).  Read was faster, average 16.48 MB/s (ranging from 16.05 to an outlier 17.46 MB/s).Now -- will these four 16GB Transcend SDHC cards perform similarly "in the real world" (ie. in my Canon G12)?  I hope so, but I don't know.  What I do know is that these cards, all four of them, far exceed the SD Association's minimum data-rate requirements for Class 10 cards of 10 MB/s, Read/Write.  Any questions?

reviewText: This card has, over the past three weeks, performed flawlessly with my Nikon D7000, which I have used to take and transfer both photos and 1080p video. If you are taking bursts of a longer duration, you may want to get a faster card. Otherwise, imho this card is plenty capable of handling most people's burst needs.Slightly off topic, but as a sub-rating, I gave this card three stars for "storage capacity" because it has a truly "average" amount of capacity...as compared to other 32 GB cards. What a silly thing to rate -- two years ago, this capacity would have been thought gigantic, and two years from now, it will be small. There is a separate rating for "value for money," which takes into account the capacity vs. price. So I'm not sure why Amazon is asking reviewers to rate "storage capacity" as an attribute. Anyone?

The price on this card is definitely better than I could find for other brands of the same size, as well.Update (07/13/12):I found a problem with this card if you're using it in a DSLR for video. I have a Canon T3i and when I shoot video sometimes (well, probably more than half of the time) it will stop recording either within seconds of hitting record or a couple minutes later. I did a search online and what it seems to be is when you go back through your card and delete certain photos or videos that aren't at the end of the sequence it leaves gaps in the memory, then when you record a video it tries to fill those gaps before continuing at the end of the memory card. Basically, I have to save everything to my computer and format my memory card while it's in my camera before doing any video shoots to make sure this doesn't happen. It seems to work fine if I do that. In theory, if you don't delete anything that's not at the end of the number sequence, it should work fine as long as you have room, but I don't always look at each picture and decide whether or not to delete it before taking another. I have read that this isn't an issue with some other brands like San Disk, but haven't tried for myself. I also don't know if this only happens with certain cameras.This is the only problem I've had with this memory card and for everything else, it works great.

reviewText: Most people look at only one number when they buy SD cards. And that's how much data the card holds. Capacity is important, but another number is just as important. Especially if you plan to shoot video.That second number is "class" - and it tells you how fast data can be written to the memory card. Most bargain cards seem to be class 4 cards. For the average snapshooter, that's no big deal. Class 4 will do nicely. But if you plan to shoot video, you need at least a class 6 card. And the faster a card can accept data, the more expensive it generally is.This 16 GB card is a class 10. In other words, HD video should be no problem. And at 16 GB, it'll hold a lot of data. I'd normally expect to pay at least twice what I did for these Transcend cards. (I bought three.) I've purchased this brand several times before, and always found their cards to be durable and reliable. This is an excellent value in a high-speed SD card.

It seemed slow when I first started using it, but I quickly found out through experimentation that the problem was a function of file size. Using L resolution and switching to M1 made a tremendous difference.  Delay was annoying with L, but imperceptible with M1.  So, if you need more rapid firing, use the medium (M 1 or 2) resolution on the camera.  If you really want it to be lightening fast, use the S (small) resolution which is also Ideal for email.

I bought 4 of these. 1 failed after 1 couple weeks of use - had read errors. Junk! I've been using 1 in a Nikon D5100 and discovered that there was a huge delay in being able to shoot the next shot. This appears to be due to a very slow write speed for the card. I've tried 2 different cards and same thing. To compare, I used a Samsung SDHC 64GB PRO UHS-1 and there is hands down no comparison - the Samsung blows the Transcend card away. There is hardly any delay between shots, which is essential for doing bursts.I also have used the Trascend cards in my Canon HR20 HD camcorder. There is occasional jitter/frame loss in complex scenes when I use this card. I suspect this is also due to the slow write speed of the card. In comparison, if I use the Samsung card in the HR20, there is no such jitter/frame loss.Finally, I've used the transcend in a simple Sony Cybershot point and shoot camera. Again, there is noticeable delay between shots. Again, I suspect due to slow write speed. The Samsung also improved reducing the delay, but not fully. So, I can't discount the possibility that that Sony camera is simply poor at being able to do multiple shots quickly.I learned the hard way that Class 10 cards are not made equal.  What irked me the most was the card that failed. I had used it in a Zoom H4N digital audio recorder which I was planning to use in a video interview. Turned out when I went to try to play the audio, the Zoom kept having issues finding the files. I put the card in the PC to see if it would have better luck. While Windows could "see" the files, it also could not open them. Eventually, Windows reported a drive issue with the card. I tried running analysis software on the card and it detected numerous errors. Piece of junk. Fortunately, I had the audio that was taken with the camcorder itself, which fortunately, had decent fidelity I could use. I am so glad I did not rely on this card for anything as the sole source. This experience alone has soured by opinion of Transcend and will probably never trust it again. Cards like the Samsung may be more expensive, but may be there's a reason these Trascend card are so cheap.

reviewText: 64GB may sound like a lot for some, until you realize how much memory some devices use.Many users of digital DSLRs use these, and if one thing eats memory, its taking lots of digital photos. And if you are recording video using a DSLR, you can use 4GB recording only a few minutes, ie. one song at a concert.You also want a card that transfers memory quickly. The '10' on the card means it transfers data much quicker than Class 6 cards. If your camera seems slow, look at your SD card, see what Class it is. That actually Does matter, especially when shooting in bursts with a digital camera, or shooting video. On some HD systems Class 6 cards are not fast enough, you need class 10.Some day soon, 64GB will be laughably small. If these are on sale, grab them.
summary: You Think 64GB is a lot? Wait...

With that said I maybe not be getting my moneys worth for video mode as you could probably just stick with a class 6 32gb if they sell one, but for me its not a big deal seeing as though the card only cost me 40 bucks which is a decent price for 32gbs!! I used to think 8 gbs was alot for photos but 32gb well serve me even better. I might purchase another one along the way. Ive researched sandisk cards and the extreme they sell that supports 30mb/s is no longer available, and there are now companies on amazon scamming people into thinking the card supports this bitrate which is sad. So I Just stick with transcend because I have bought from them in the past and they are of good quality. I probably average around 20mb/s on this card but the only way to really test its class 10 status, is by downloading magic lantern and testing it out on the qscale.

Re-formatted and still doesn't solve the flickers. Even when I remove Magic Lantern and turn off all auto adjustments and custom funtions (auto focus, auto white balance, auto exposure, highlight tone priority, etc), I still get them. It's very annoying.I've tested the card with CDM3's software and found out the read speed is a bit over 19Mb/s and the write speed is a bit over 16Mb/s. I think the flicker is due to the card's slow write speed. I'm going to buy a Sandisk Extreme and see if it gets rid of my problem. I will write an update when I get my Sandisk card.Update 2: Turns out the flickering was because of Apple's preview window (the window that pops up when you press space bar on a media file). The Transcend captures 1080 25p video without any hick-ups. That's at the standard stock bit rate though, if you use Magic Lantern to crank it any higher, it'll frequently stop your recording. The Sandisk Extreme that I purchased can handle 3.0 CBR with audio on (at least for me it does).

I bought this because we needed more storage in our Wii.  We had a 1 GB card but that was mostly filled - we've purchased a number of downloadable games and hardly had any space to download any more games or demos.Moving the content from one card to another was a minor chore: first I inserted this card into the Wii, turned on the Wii, and moved (not copied) everything from system memory to this card.  I then turned off the Wii, inserted the old SD card, turned the Wii on, and moved as much as I could from the old SD card to the Wii.  Powering down the Wii, I inserted this card again, turned on the Wii, moved everything from system memory to this card...over and over until the old SD card was empty.  Phew!Now that everything's copied the card works as expected.  We can launch directly from the card and all thumbnails show up like they should.  No problems with this card and the Wii.Note that SD cards larger than 2 GB require Wii system menu 4.0 or higher to work.  If you've been doing system updates as they come out you'll be fine (we have version 4.3 right now) but if your Wii isn't connected to the Internet you'll have to update your system manually; see Nintendo's site for instructions.As an aside, Amazon's frustration-free packaging is great.  This card was in a plastic SD card protective case, which was in a thin cardboard envelope along with instructions and warranty information.  I unzipped the envelope, recycled it, and I was ready to go.

In fairness I have to say I've used Transcend cards over the years without incident or problems.However based on some of the reviews here - I think it's fair to say the class 10 really does have a speed rate of a class 6 according to clocking by any number of sources. However to me this was pretty much a non issue when deciding to by another 64 GB for my Panasonic HMC40P entry level Pro video camera.The first version of this particular cam could only take up to 32GB cards - but you can now bump it up to as high as 128 GB. When the card arrived it took multiple efforts to format - as I dug deeper into the reviews albeit most are positive the complaints were pretty much all the same:* Trouble formatting* Cameras not turning off* Distortion and surprisingly slow rendering time for a class 10My first inclination was that the problem was within the cameras card reader so I placed a call to Panasonic Pro cam support. The feedback I received was in a nut shell to stick with Sandisc as they've had numerous calls regarding problems with the Transcend cards.Bottom line - these cards may be less expensive but cheaper of course never means better. I think for certain applications Transcend is still a find choice for low to mid level cameras and camcorders. However as the tech I spoke with put it - when you've spent 2 grand on a camera - don't skimp on the memory cards.
summary: Problematic 64GB Card - Tough To Format Poor Perfomance

Why I Bought This Particular Card-1) I have had good luck with this brand on cross-platform uses (Mac & PC) The one time I needed tech support, I was on hold for about one minute & actually received an answer from someone I could understand.2) I wanted a faster card for data transfer between computers.3) My existing (non Transcend) camera card is getting pretty wonky & unreliable.4) This card kind of covered all the above bases at a reasonable price.What I Found Out While Testing (And goofing around):In The MacBook Pro Running OS X 10.6.8- Card Formatted To FAT 32Reliability: This card works fine for moving large files between computers. I've had no files corrupted nor lost.Speed: Scary Fast. Remember, the speed will be limited by the card  reader & the bus speed of the machine.Initialization: Instant recognition by the Mac. Available immediately. OS X is so cool about fast access.In The MacBook Pro Card Formatted For Mac Only (OS X Extended Journaled)- Same results as FAT 32 (But, of course, no Windows transfers)In The Virtual PC Running XP Pro via Virtual Box-No Problems. Same as the Mac, but slower initialization. All devices are recognized faster on Unix based machines than Windows.In The VIrtual PC Running Windows 98SE-Windows 98SE got kind of crabby about this card. To be fair, it complains about everything USB.It kinda-Sorta works, but does not set any speed records. It is recognized as 512mb, but I put 4 gb of data on it without problems.In Windows 98SE on a physical machine- This card was not recognized. But... I did not attempt to find a solution. No Comment.In The Canon A590is Camera-Reliability: I have not lost any photos. But, regardless of which card I use, I would never trust valuable photos to just onecard. Ideally, split them up. Share the risk.Initialization: This card is slower to be available than my class 4 cards.I would imagine, quite simply, because it is a bigger storage device for the camera to 'study'.On the class 4 256mb card, with no data- It takes less than one second for the camera to recognize the card & let it be accessed.On this class 10 8mb card, with no data- The camera takes about 5 seconds to allow the card to be used. Big deal, huh?Recording Photos: I set the camera to its largest file format of 3264x2448 least compression (3.436mb)I was able to take more than one photo per second. It went too fast for me to time.The speed stayed consistant from empty card to full card. (Which was a ton of photos.)On-Camera playback was equally as fast.For Reference- With the MMC card that came with the camera- I can shoot one photo on this resolution every 3-4 seconds.Recording Video: The card worked fine. I filled it up & played back a captivating movie about my workshop. Ooh! Ahh!The card performed very well. There was no jumping & no fluttering on the video.In The Printer-  Brother MFC- J6710DWDirectly In The Printer's Card Slot- Recognized & available immediately. Scrolling was the same speed as my other cards.I suppose the scrolling speed is the limitation of the printer. (For the record- Less about one second between photos)In The Printer's USB Slot Via A Card Reader- Noticeably slower. This must be the reader or the printer's bus.Would I Buy Another-Yes- Without Hesitation
summary: Works Fine In Mac, Windows XP Pro and In Canon A590is Camera

reviewText: I ran a test using ATTO Benchmark on a USB 2.0 Card Reader with all read/write buffering disabled and got 18.1 MB/sec writes and 19.9 MB/sec reads. That's more than enough for what I need.I bought a pair of these 32GB cards for aCanon PowerShot S100 12.1 MP Digital Camera with 5x Wide Angle Optical Image Stabilized Zoom (Black). Both cards worked fine out of the box. Their performance exceeds the demands of this camera and there are no delays attributable to the card. I've tested HD Video, Super Slow Motion at 120fps and 240fps, 2.3 fps continuous full-resolution shooting, fast single-shot pictures, and Hi-Speed Burst HQ mode. In burst mode, the camera takes 8 full resolution pictures in under 1 second, then the activity light blinks for just over 3 seconds as the pictures are processed and stored. I've tested the burst with simple scenes (1 MB per photo) and detailed scenes (4.5 MB per photo) and there is no performance difference, so the SDHC card is not the bottleneck.I'm perfectly happy with these cards. I've used various Transcend SDHC and CF cards for compacts and DSLRs for 50,000+ photos and never had a problem with them, so I trust the brand and find the price/performance to be a perfect fit for high-end consumer cameras.
summary: Good price/performance, works perfectly with Canon S100

This Transcend SDHC card is high capacity with 3 2GB.  It also has quick speed (20 MB per second its cards read speed with its write speed being 16 MB per second). It is a high quality card.  All this and a reasonable price.  It has it all.After some research, I discovered that these cards have a "Class," something I was not aware of before. Therefore, this Class 10 Transcdend, the top of the line, fit the bill.  This Class 10 has not disappointed after more than a year now.  I performs flawlessly.  Class 10 is for sustaining a minimum speed of 10 MBPS, and it performs above this levelI bought this card for a SimplyVibe portable music player I have. I had a 16 GB card I was using and I was quickly running out of space, and I was having lag time issues with some of my files loading. That was it; I was going to get a 32 GB card.  As for space, I have almost 6,000 songs on my card and it still has almost 2 GB of space remaining.  I did not think a card could hold so much.After more than a year in my music player, I can tell you, this thing is FAST. There is absolutely no lag time in loading music files.Overall, this was a great buy, and a great value.  No other SDHC card in Class 10 could come close to the reasonable price of this Transcend card.

I recently purchased a Canon SX40 camera and this card along with it.  I have never had a memory card error before, but there's a first time for everything.  It didn't start right away.  I took about 70 pictures and 2 videos before things started to slowly crumble.  On a couple of photos, the camera could not view them and called them "unidentified images".  When uploaded to a computer, those photos did transfer, but strangely only 1/2 the picture showed up.  Then the total breakdown occurred when the camera simply told me "memory card error".  I couldn't view any images, nor upload any that hadn't been.  I originally put the blame on the camera, which was clearly wrong.  Camera's fine.  Couldn't be better actually, now that that card is out.I contacted Transcend and they directed me to their website where they have a lost data recovery program for download called "RecoveRx".  I downloaded it and gave it a try and it did recover most of my photos.  It took the program about 9 hours of running time to do this btw.  Unfortunately, not all pics were recovered and definitely not the videos (which were the most important things on the card!).  I sent the card in to Transcend and they are in the process of sending me a new card...which will work this time...right?  The only way one can professionally have their memory card resurrected would be to send it overseas to the tune of 3 months processing time plus who knows how much $.  I weighed the cost and time to the need to get those videos back and it just didn't add up.  So I cut my losses and am getting a new card.  I am certainly gun shy at this point though in shooting photos.  I'm sure things will turn out fine in the end, but I'm longing for the days when the only way you could lose your photos was to open the back of your camera by accident!Best of luck to other Transcend card users out there, of which there must be quite a few.

reviewText: Lets face it.  That high end camera that you bought is a bit excessive, but you deserved it, so you got it.  Then you took it on the trip.  The first day you stumbled a bit taking pictures, but the second day you got the hang of it and captured some great shots.  Maybe you've discovered that you are an avid wild life photographer or maybe you are infatuated with the textures of the world around you, whatever it was, by the third day you were out of space on you little memory card, and spent almost half a battery panning through and deleting enough pictures so that you could keep that masterful picture of the dessert that you had last night.  Well my friend, enter this card.  With this memory card you can have enough space for pictures of every darling thing your kids or grandkids might do, plus the artful shots of that latte that you had for breakfast, some of the fantastic scenery that surrounds you, and a few blurry shots or photobombs too.  You know you need it, Add To Cart
Like every other Transcend card I've gotten, this one is flawless.  I've bought a number of Transcend SD and Micro SD cards over the past few years.  All are still in use and all work perfectly.
This is a great card for an awesome price! I'm using it without any problems in a Canon EOS 6D.

The warranty info says to register it at transcend-info.com/warranty within 30 days of purchase for better chance of coverage.Hopefully if my card does eventually die from its use in my RPi, Transcend honors the lifetime warranty. My video would stop recording at 14 seconds because the card could not be written to fast enough to clear the buffer. HD video uses a lot of data and needs a high speed card. Look not at the 200X, 400X speed, but the millisecond transfer rate. I got a 95ms card and it never bogs down. I got some 40 ms cards and they work fine as well. In HD video speed is king, so make sure the card you buy meets your purposes.

reviewText: I purchased this card to use with my Canon HF S10 Camcorder. (Note: Several of the Canon Vixia camcorders require a firmware upgrade to be able to uses class 10 memory cards instead of class 6, some are available as downloads from Canon's website, others such as mine require the camcorder to be sent in for a free upgrade to use these cards). It has worked well for me both using it to record in maximum 1920X1080P resolution for a 2 hours Van Halen concert and I have also used this to store large amounts of data on.  Memory cars keep getting cheaper and the 26.99 for this seems like a fair price for a 32 Gig class 10 card. I have seen an HP go on sale for $22.00 recently on Amazon but this is one of the recommended brands according to Canaon so it was worth the money to me for sure.It has a fast write speed and from looking through reviews it seems to be a stable card so combined with the price I think it is a great deal.  32 Gigs is enough to store 2 1/2 hours of Blu Ray quality resolution on my camcorder.  I have the extended battery for it so I can really record quite a bit of continuous video so the size and combination of power and capacity work out great for me.  Considering that these cards are inexpensive, high quality and reusable all at a low price makes them a great deal for anyone needing a reliable class 10 32 Gig SDHC card.No problems dealing with it installed in my camcorder or transferring files from the card to my computer yet so I am satisfied.
summary: Good SDHC card bought on sale

reviewText: I use this with my Canon EOS Rebel T3 camera. 16gb is more than adequate for my kind of photography (airplanes, wildlife), both still and video. I've never come close to filling it up.

I've never had a problem with Transcend memory cards in the past--I've been using them for years without fault. I assumed that with a 20MB/S rate and 8GB of memory, I wouldn't have any issues recording videos with my T2i. I'm not sure if my card in particular was defective, but the card was too low-quality to capture video, even with the lowest frame rate possible.I wouldn't call this "class 10", and I wouldn't say it shoots 20MB/S. Can it record videos? Whelp, mine can't. Can it take photos rapidly? Yes. Does it have a lot of memory? Yes. Will it work beautifully with non-DSLR cameras? Yes.Bottom Line: If you want to unlock the true potential of your DSLR, spend a little more for a higher quality card (it really does make a difference). If you want a reliable card that takes photos fine, by all means go ahead and buy this one. Makes for a reliable, cheap backup memory card.
summary: If using a DSLR, do NOT use for videos

I have used Transcend memory for my full size DLSR before with no issues at all.  I bought a few of them for my HD camcorder HC V700 so I will never run out of memory for my long travel trips. They are not as fast as Sandisk, but price wise it is about about 40% cheaper. Be aware that the transfer (write/read) is slower than the Sandisk Extreme, but it is more than enough for my camcorder. Check with your equipment to see what is the minimum write speed requirement and check with the manufacturer specifications, and avoid the reliance in Class rating. for my purpose, it serves well.

I have no problem taking photos and video with this memory card.  32GB is also huge, as I can take about 5,500 pictures at 14.1MP size.  I had trouble using it to transfer files from my desktop to my laptop (both running Win7), as the desktop kept wanting to scan the card for errors, and it didn't transfer all my files to the card.  I reformatted the card, and that didn't help.  The error message it was giving me is more common with hard drives, saying the destination can't be found, the original folder doesn't exist, etc.  But I didn't have any problem at all with my laptop, so I think the problem is with my desktop.  I ended up using a thumb drive to transfer the files.  But as far as using it in my camera, no problem.
I Bought this SD card for my Tascam DP-008 mixer or recorder. It did the job well in storing the audio files.

I purchased a Transcend 32GB card for my DSLR.The card works fine in the camera, seems to record video and burst-shot stills at a rate that does not limit my camera (Nikon D90).However, whenever the card is inserted into an SD card reader, it is unwritable. (No, the lock tab is not enabled)I have tried disk utilities in OS X, Windows XP, and Ubuntu Linux and none are able to reconfigure this card.When photos are copied from the card to a computer, they have to be "unprotected" before one can edit them. While this adds time to photo processing, it can be done in batch (if one knows how to do this).This problem prevents one from updating camera firmware or adding custom controls to a camera.Internet searches show this a common problem with Transcend cards and no "solution" offered by those wanting to be helpful works.I'm buying a SanDisk card for my regular use and will keep the Transcend as an emergency back-up for the camera.

I'm using this for music in the car. It's the perfect size to fit my music collection and playlists for using on my car's Uconnect system. I occasionally get a read error, but not sure if it is the SD card or the Uconnect. I don't get the error when using it with my computer.
It is a good card for its price! Not pricey and for normal point and shoot photography? More than good! Great buy

reviewText: I think with things like this you're always taking a gamble.  In this case I'm using a Canon T2i and I bought this card for video shooting.  I already own a Patriot 16GB class 10 card which works beautifully and very consistently for me.  I bought this Transcend card based on value and reviews I read.  After having used it for a couple days I have to admit I'm disappointed.  For stills, it's fine.  For video?  Not so much.  It is constantly failing on me.  I'm also receiving a camera error when using this specific card in which I cannot shoot any video at all sometimes.  Despite formatting the card a few times, the problem persists.  This does not happen with the other cards I have from other manufacturers.  I can't say I know exactly what the problem is but I don't really care about that.  What matters is that it only happens with this card in the camera.  I bought this card so I could shoot more video with the greater storage capacity.  Needless to say, I think I'm going to just get another Patriot card at 32GB and try that while keeping this card for stills at least.  Nothing wrong with it for that.
Need one SD card for my camcorder. So I simply choose the recommended one in the package deal Amazon provided.It is ok, it does everything you could expect from an SD card. Nothing to complain. :)
good quality and fast on HD video. The price was great and transcend is one of the leading makers of SD cards

I purchased a few Transcend SDHC cards from Amazon's "Warehouse Deals".  The cards I chose were labeled as "used", ... and I could tell from the somewhat-sloppy taped-cardboard package that they arrived in that they had been returned to Amazon by others.  However, the low-prices I paid for these cards were a fraction of the "regular price" of these cards, ... and aside from the packaging, the cards looked "new", and function perfectly.  (I used my Mac's Disc Utility to erase and re-format the cards, and they've been working flawlessly).  I'm happy Amazon offers this option to purchase "used" cards.

I bought this to use for making street videos with my Panasonic Lumix GF1 Micro Four Thirds. I am delighted and now will probably get one for my Nikon D7000. Unless I go for even bigger. In video, size matters.

reviewText: This card is a great buy.  The price is reasonable, and works great with my Nikon D7000.  I can't take more than 9 pictures in rapid fire but that may be because of the large size of each file.  Still nine shots is a lot.  Cards works without a hitch and I am saving a lot of money.

It is also slower then the other brands I have used but not intolerably.  Would have spent a little more to get the bigger size if I'd known, I tried to find an example of how many pics it would hold in reviews but their cameras must save data more efficiently because I was much lower in capacity.
It's still working to this day. I bought it last year in August and it still works, no failures or anything.

This memory card has served me well. I wanted class 10, 32 GB SDHC memory cards, but was shocked at the cost of name brand manufacturers. This is a value priced card that does what it is supposed to do without glitches or struggle. I have purchased at least 6 of these in the last couple years and have been happy with them all. For an average point and shoot camera, these store a ridiculous number of pictures. One thing to make sure is that your device is SDHC memory card compatible, I know that sounds obvious, but it bit me once with an older point and shoot that I stuffed one of these SDHC cards in. I'm confident that this brand in a lower class would be a good bet as well, and even cheaper.

No issues - bought to use with my Cannon HD videocam.  I can get 2 hours of MP4 video on this card (typical length of one of my son's baseball games).  The locking mechanism slips into lock mode at times when I insert into my PC's card reader.  I just put a piece of tape over it and no more issues.

reviewText: I purchased a similar Transcend 8GD SDHC Class 10 memory card a few months ago. It came with a small plastic case to protect the memory card when not in use. I'm not sure if Transcend has changed the packaging for ALL of their products, but this 16GB Class 10 card arrived in a very small plastic "blister pack," without a plastic storage case. You can easily remove the plastic "blister pack from the cardboard...it pulls right out, but it is a "poor man's" substitute for the real thing!Performance wise I have had no problems with Transcend products and I in fact use their computer memory modules in critical embedded computing applications at my business. So, I will give this product Five Stars, with the caveat you need a spare storage case to put in.
summary: Good Price & Performance...But No Plastic Storage Case

reviewText: Great value--thanks, Amazon!  Works great in my new camera--no complaints.  Lots of storage space, too.  Very happy with this product.

I have a few of these cards and a Sandisk Extreme card as well. All are 16GB. I understand that professional photographers with the multi thousand dollar cameras may need a card as fast as the Extreme. However, for 95% of users, this Transcend Class 10 SDHC should be more than enough.I have a Canon T2i DSLR that I use to take lots of high resolution photos and 1080p HD video. This card never slows down. Even in burst mode, I have to take at LEAST 40 photos before the card stops to write- it's that fast. It also works great for HD video.Is this card a super high end professional series memory card? No, but it's not marketed that way. For casual DSLR users or people with HD video cameras, this card is great. Speed has never been an issue for me. The fact that frustration free packaging was available is icing on the cake.

I've heard that often Class 10 cards die when you overclock your Pi. I'm using the following settings:arm_freq=1000gpu_mem=128avoid_safe_mode=1core_freq=500sdram_freq=500over_voltage=4force_turbo=0So far the Transcend card is holding up great! I have yet to experience any issues. If something happens I'll come back and post. Great value and I'll probably get another one for a different Pi project!
This works in my Canon PowerShot A2500 16MP Digital Camera with 2.7-Inch LCD very well and in my toshiba laptop to transfer the pictures.
summary: Works in my Canon PowerShot A2500 16MP Digital Camera with 2.7-Inch LCD very well

reviewText: I have many, many of these Transcend 32GB cards and have never had a problem.  The price is low enough that I can store them as additional backup, or use them for delivery to clients.

Works well with my 5D mark III (15 RAW shots before the buffer gets full)Measured transfer speeds via an internal PCI-E card reader (USB 3.0 ready):- write: 17MBs- read:  24MB/sTherefore the card can be considered compliant with the advertised speeds and with the Class 10 specs.Happy for the time being and no need to upgrade until the next Black Friday deal :)

I found the Transcend to offer very good performance.  Both read and writes were faster than the class 10 base rating.  I was especially impressed at the fast write speeds, which is really crucial for recording large amounts of data.  Still SD cards really can't keep up with CF cards...albeit you pay a premium for CF, so that should be expected.These are tests I ran on my own system.  Nothing fancy, just copying a large file from local HD to memory card, and then back from memory card to HD.Notes:Kingston's USB 3.0 Media Reader Computer Memory FCR-HS3Plugable PCI Express to SuperSpeed USB 3.0 2-Port Expansion Card for Desktops (NEC/Renesas Chipset)Windows 7 64bit2.79 GB file transfer from local HD to memory cardI took the average reading from the last 15 seconds of data transferSECURE DIGITALSandisk Ultra 64gb (rated 30 MB/s)Write 12.6 MB/sRead 40.2 MB/sTranscend 32gb (rated ?)Write 18.7 MB/sRead 21.8 MB/sPatriot LX Series 32gb (rated ?)Write 11.0 MB/sRead 22.3 MB/sCOMPACT FLASHLexar UDMA 7 CF 64gb (rated 400x)Write 58.2 MB/sRead 106.0 MB/s
summary: Fast write compared to other more expensive cards.

A dollar per gigabyte? How can you go wrong? For the most part, you can't. But if you do high-resolution continuous shooting, it's going to slow you down. With a 16 megapixel Sony Nex-5n set to store RAW plus fine JPEG, the camera fires off a quick half dozen shots, then slows to about one per second. With fine JPEG only, I got 10 or so shots in a 1-second burst, then about 2 per second thereafter. Standard JPEG is only marginally better.The good news is that I never shoot burst/continuous, so this isn't an issue for me. These cards are so inexpensive you could just file them away when you fill them and leave it to future generations to sort out your images.The other good news is that I can shoot HD video (60p) on these cards with the Nex 5n or on my Canon Vixia HF M40 camcorder. That's good enough for me.

First let me start by saying I have a little expierience with these sdhc memory cards and have tested a good deal of them now. Not all of them perform at their rated speed like they advertise! But this transcend is very close to its specs. It says its read speed is 20mb/s and its write speed being 16mb/s and its very very close to those marks on my tests. This places it at one of the top ones on my list for the overall price and performance. Now with that said I wouldnt recommend it for a high end SLR that has super high speed shooting(like a few others also state) but for an overall point and shoot digital camera its going to be perfect. Overall Im very pleased with this and the price makes it even better, 5 stars!

This is the first and last time I purchase transcend products.  This was recommended by Amazon to go with my purchase of the Canon Powershot SX50 HS digital camera - all purchases through Amazon.  Worked great until yesterday, pretty much 6 months later.  I am trying to recover my photos now with their recovery tool, now an hour into the process.  I am not sure if it will work.  They say lifetime warranty when it does not even last a year?  This is the first time that I use SDHC cards.  I just purchased a Sandisk SDHC card to replace the Trasncend.  I already have a Sandisk SDHC for my digital camcorder and no problems at all (so far).  I believe that any card without the speeds noted end up not working from reading all the various reviews across different brands, especially Transcend.  The Transcend website is a bit difficult to navigate, probably due to the issues.  I am trying to see what remedy I have with "lifetime" warranty since I assume a new card would do the same thing again.  I shall attempt to reformat to maybe use as a back up memory card as a worse case scenario.
summary: Worked great at beginning and now memory card error after 6 months
